00:00:29.045 --> 00:00:29.995
Thanks, everybody.

00:00:32.845 --> 00:00:34.221
Sounds like my mic is on.

00:00:34.221 --> 00:00:34.720
Yeah?

00:00:34.720 --> 00:00:36.110
You can hear me OK?

00:00:36.110 --> 00:00:39.090
Well, first of all, thank
you, Adam, for having me.

00:00:39.090 --> 00:00:40.100
It's such a pleasure.

00:00:40.100 --> 00:00:42.900
And I told him that I've
been on the Google campus

00:00:42.900 --> 00:00:43.810
now for two days.

00:00:43.810 --> 00:00:46.760
We did some training
work two days ago.

00:00:46.760 --> 00:00:49.630
I facilitated a team
meeting all day yesterday.

00:00:49.630 --> 00:00:52.434
And I've decided that
Google is the mecca.

00:00:52.434 --> 00:00:53.850
People need to
come to Google just

00:00:53.850 --> 00:00:56.990
to find out in what domain
you need to upgrade your life.

00:00:56.990 --> 00:00:58.680
You can figure
out what foods you

00:00:58.680 --> 00:01:02.650
should be eating, what physical
practices you should have,

00:01:02.650 --> 00:01:04.500
what kinds of
technology is available.

00:01:04.500 --> 00:01:08.330
It's so exciting and wondrous,
from one point of view.

00:01:08.330 --> 00:01:10.100
I mean, it's really
kind of miraculous

00:01:10.100 --> 00:01:13.600
how many movements and
culture, like different kinds

00:01:13.600 --> 00:01:16.770
of movements have found
their home here and held

00:01:16.770 --> 00:01:19.980
in what used to be considered
a corporate setting.

00:01:19.980 --> 00:01:21.860
I think it would be
hard to call it that.

00:01:21.860 --> 00:01:24.860
I'm not quite sure what the new
language is, but just the sense

00:01:24.860 --> 00:01:26.870
that you're actually
really integrated and alive

00:01:26.870 --> 00:01:31.070
and enjoying being
a human being.

00:01:31.070 --> 00:01:32.570
So I wrote a book.

00:01:32.570 --> 00:01:34.580
And my book was
published last December.

00:01:34.580 --> 00:01:36.746
And I think there were going
to be some copies here.

00:01:36.746 --> 00:01:38.060
They may still be arriving.

00:01:38.060 --> 00:01:40.450
The book is called
"Everything is Workable."

00:01:40.450 --> 00:01:44.250
And there's a really beautiful
publisher out of Boston

00:01:44.250 --> 00:01:46.220
called Shambhala Publications.

00:01:46.220 --> 00:01:47.850
Do any of you know
Shambhala Books?

00:01:47.850 --> 00:01:48.350
Yeah.

00:01:48.350 --> 00:01:50.780
So Shambhala is
interesting, because they

00:01:50.780 --> 00:01:53.900
were one of the first
companies way back in, I think,

00:01:53.900 --> 00:01:57.180
the early '60s or
'70s to really want

00:01:57.180 --> 00:02:00.560
to bring the wisdom of
the East to the West.

00:02:00.560 --> 00:02:04.490
And so they were
devoted to Zen texts.

00:02:04.490 --> 00:02:07.970
They were devoted to
sort of Asian wisdom.

00:02:07.970 --> 00:02:10.349
And there was also a book
that really made the company.

00:02:10.349 --> 00:02:11.640
I don't know if you know of it.

00:02:11.640 --> 00:02:15.100
The book was called "The
Art of War" by Sun Tzu.

00:02:15.100 --> 00:02:17.940
So that book was translated
and published in English

00:02:17.940 --> 00:02:19.260
first by Shambhala.

00:02:19.260 --> 00:02:22.970
And basically, as
I understand it,

00:02:22.970 --> 00:02:25.600
was the financial success
point for that company.

00:02:25.600 --> 00:02:28.010
So I was really privileged
to be approached by Shambhala

00:02:28.010 --> 00:02:32.460
and asked as a meditation
teacher, Zen practitioner,

00:02:32.460 --> 00:02:35.890
and also a mediator, whether
I was interested in working

00:02:35.890 --> 00:02:38.060
with them to bring
something into print.

00:02:38.060 --> 00:02:42.290
So really, if you think
about the word "meditation,"

00:02:42.290 --> 00:02:47.380
the word "meditation" has that
root, "med-" in it, I think,

00:02:47.380 --> 00:02:48.770
which is probably Latin.

00:02:48.770 --> 00:02:51.790
Does anybody know actually how
it translates from the Latin?

00:02:51.790 --> 00:02:53.360
I don't know exactly.

00:02:53.360 --> 00:02:57.070
But "meditate" and
"mediate" both literally

00:02:57.070 --> 00:02:59.950
mean "to bring two into one."

00:02:59.950 --> 00:03:03.780
So with meditation, when
you sit down on the cushion,

00:03:03.780 --> 00:03:05.980
you're bringing your
body, speech, and mind

00:03:05.980 --> 00:03:07.190
into one moment.

00:03:07.190 --> 00:03:09.560
And you're creating
coherence with your life.

00:03:09.560 --> 00:03:12.490
So you could say meditation
is a way of becoming one

00:03:12.490 --> 00:03:15.170
with your life,
whereas mediation

00:03:15.170 --> 00:03:17.980
is about bringing two
differing points of view

00:03:17.980 --> 00:03:21.300
or two different sets of
interests or a conflict

00:03:21.300 --> 00:03:24.500
in which there are many
parties into one solution.

00:03:24.500 --> 00:03:27.180
So the impulse of
meditation and of mediation

00:03:27.180 --> 00:03:28.970
are really the same impulse.

00:03:28.970 --> 00:03:33.010
And so I gave a lot of thought
to both internal conflict

00:03:33.010 --> 00:03:35.350
and also the conflict
that we experience,

00:03:35.350 --> 00:03:38.850
both in our personal
lives and also culturally,

00:03:38.850 --> 00:03:42.300
and you might even
say on a global scale,

00:03:42.300 --> 00:03:45.210
and gave a lot of consideration
to how we work with conflict,

00:03:45.210 --> 00:03:47.820
both within ourselves
and outside of ourselves.

00:03:47.820 --> 00:03:51.610
And I wanted to make
the point that conflict,

00:03:51.610 --> 00:03:55.380
while it is
uncomfortable, is actually

00:03:55.380 --> 00:03:58.550
an incredible developmental
opportunity, that there

00:03:58.550 --> 00:04:01.080
are things that can come
from conflict when you work

00:04:01.080 --> 00:04:03.280
with it in an innovative way.

00:04:03.280 --> 00:04:06.610
And because you are really
a culture of innovators,

00:04:06.610 --> 00:04:10.360
that working with conflict
from a creative point of view

00:04:10.360 --> 00:04:12.770
is-- there's an incredible
amount of growth,

00:04:12.770 --> 00:04:14.490
possibility, and
new solutions that

00:04:14.490 --> 00:04:18.390
can come from it when we
include it as potential.

00:04:18.390 --> 00:04:20.329
The issue that we
have with conflict

00:04:20.329 --> 00:04:23.630
is that the old
hardware, if you will--

00:04:23.630 --> 00:04:25.790
I'm going to try to use
some of your language

00:04:25.790 --> 00:04:29.480
and it's going to be kind of
pathetic, so just work with me.

00:04:29.480 --> 00:04:32.880
So the old evolutionary
hardware does not

00:04:32.880 --> 00:04:35.010
give you the
sensation in your body

00:04:35.010 --> 00:04:37.630
that this is a creative
opportunity, right?

00:04:37.630 --> 00:04:41.169
When the tri-brain-- we
have the reptilian brain,

00:04:41.169 --> 00:04:42.960
the mammalian brain,
and the primate brain.

00:04:42.960 --> 00:04:45.964
And when the reptilian brain
senses a threat-- which

00:04:45.964 --> 00:04:47.880
whenever there's a
conflict, there's a threat.

00:04:47.880 --> 00:04:49.990
There's a threat to our
resources, our identity,

00:04:49.990 --> 00:04:54.910
our physical well-being,
the stability of our life.

00:04:54.910 --> 00:04:59.070
Conflict is, by its nature,
threatening to the status quo.

00:04:59.070 --> 00:05:01.150
So because it's
threatening, what happens

00:05:01.150 --> 00:05:03.700
is that these chemical--
that the reptilian brain

00:05:03.700 --> 00:05:05.350
stimulates the amygdala.

00:05:05.350 --> 00:05:09.420
And the amygdala is
the signal function

00:05:09.420 --> 00:05:13.120
behind the eyes that
stimulates the rest of the body

00:05:13.120 --> 00:05:14.860
to fight or flight or freeze.

00:05:14.860 --> 00:05:19.280
So you get this chemical dump
of cortisol, of adrenaline.

00:05:19.280 --> 00:05:22.710
And so your later
brain can say, oh

00:05:22.710 --> 00:05:25.430
great-- creative opportunity.

00:05:25.430 --> 00:05:28.450
But your body is saying, I'm
getting out of here, right?

00:05:28.450 --> 00:05:31.770
I'm going to fight, flight, or
disappear-- one or the other.

00:05:31.770 --> 00:05:33.800
And so we have this problem.

00:05:33.800 --> 00:05:38.010
We have this problem that
the sensation of conflict

00:05:38.010 --> 00:05:40.670
does not support this notion
that it's an opportunity,

00:05:40.670 --> 00:05:42.360
that it's a creative
possibility.

00:05:42.360 --> 00:05:45.940
Because everything in our body
wants to get away from it.

00:05:45.940 --> 00:05:49.040
The sensations of conflict,
no matter what you do,

00:05:49.040 --> 00:05:50.740
do not feel good.

00:05:50.740 --> 00:05:54.660
And so with enough practice,
you can override that sensation.

00:05:54.660 --> 00:05:56.870
You can start to
wire, if you will,

00:05:56.870 --> 00:06:00.330
the reptilian response to
these higher functions of mind.

00:06:00.330 --> 00:06:03.650
And you can habituate
yourself to reinterpreting it.

00:06:03.650 --> 00:06:05.870
And you can do a
counter-intuitive

00:06:05.870 --> 00:06:07.725
starting to move towards it.

00:06:07.725 --> 00:06:09.100
But there's so
much that you have

00:06:09.100 --> 00:06:12.210
to kind of be able to
master in your own body

00:06:12.210 --> 00:06:13.730
and also in your thoughts.

00:06:13.730 --> 00:06:15.110
Because generally,
as soon as you

00:06:15.110 --> 00:06:19.340
start to have the negative
sensations of adrenaline

00:06:19.340 --> 00:06:22.174
and cortisol, usually
the cognitions follow.

00:06:22.174 --> 00:06:23.840
In other words, your
thoughts are, like,

00:06:23.840 --> 00:06:26.190
ooh, I don't want to be
here, why is this happening,

00:06:26.190 --> 00:06:28.580
that person is wrong,
this should stop.

00:06:28.580 --> 00:06:31.180
So generally, your
thoughts and your body

00:06:31.180 --> 00:06:33.380
both wire to get you
out of the situation.

00:06:33.380 --> 00:06:35.090
Does that make
sense to everybody,

00:06:35.090 --> 00:06:36.240
what it is I'm saying?

00:06:36.240 --> 00:06:36.370
Yeah?

00:06:36.370 --> 00:06:37.870
AUDIENCE: Does the
reverse also hold

00:06:37.870 --> 00:06:40.495
true, where your thoughts
can then [INAUDIBLE]?

00:06:40.495 --> 00:06:41.870
DIANE MUSHO
HAMILTON: Absolutely.

00:06:41.870 --> 00:06:43.620
And that's really what
we're working with,

00:06:43.620 --> 00:06:46.630
is that what happens is you
enter into a feedback loop.

00:06:46.630 --> 00:06:48.640
So when you work with
people with conflict,

00:06:48.640 --> 00:06:51.870
one of the things that you have
to do is you have to-- well,

00:06:51.870 --> 00:06:53.370
I'll give you an
example that's more

00:06:53.370 --> 00:06:54.720
related to my own experience.

00:06:54.720 --> 00:06:56.530
So there's a chapter in my book.

00:06:56.530 --> 00:06:59.680
I was remarried, oh,
it's been now 15 years.

00:06:59.680 --> 00:07:03.360
And I remarried a man
who had three daughters,

00:07:03.360 --> 00:07:04.860
and their mother had died.

00:07:04.860 --> 00:07:07.920
And I had one-- I have one son.

00:07:07.920 --> 00:07:09.340
My son also has Down syndrome.

00:07:09.340 --> 00:07:12.560
He's a genius.

00:07:12.560 --> 00:07:16.770
And so we came together, and it
was incredibly intense for me,

00:07:16.770 --> 00:07:19.820
because they hadn't had a female
in the household for five years

00:07:19.820 --> 00:07:21.150
since their mother died.

00:07:21.150 --> 00:07:24.420
They were all at different
ages-- 16, 13, 9.

00:07:24.420 --> 00:07:27.090
It was really challenging
emotionally for me,

00:07:27.090 --> 00:07:30.790
both to merge into the culture
but also to kind of create

00:07:30.790 --> 00:07:33.020
certain kinds of
organization and patterning

00:07:33.020 --> 00:07:35.020
that would work for
everyone, including me.

00:07:35.020 --> 00:07:36.670
Mostly, that wasn't happening.

00:07:36.670 --> 00:07:40.050
So I would just feel
overwhelmed, irritable.

00:07:40.050 --> 00:07:41.820
I was losing my temper.

00:07:41.820 --> 00:07:44.400
I just was starting,
really, to experience myself

00:07:44.400 --> 00:07:47.680
in a way that was just
really not acceptable.

00:07:47.680 --> 00:07:49.530
So I developed a
practice that when

00:07:49.530 --> 00:07:52.150
I started to feel really
tense and really stressed,

00:07:52.150 --> 00:07:54.830
and that amygdala hijack
started to happen,

00:07:54.830 --> 00:07:56.940
that I would immediately
go upstairs to my room,

00:07:56.940 --> 00:07:58.330
and I would sit down.

00:07:58.330 --> 00:08:01.840
And the first thing I would
do is quiet my thinking mind

00:08:01.840 --> 00:08:04.560
and just sit with the
intensity of the sensation.

00:08:04.560 --> 00:08:06.120
Like where was I feeling this?

00:08:06.120 --> 00:08:08.210
I could feel the increase
in my heart rate.

00:08:08.210 --> 00:08:09.960
I would feel heat in my neck.

00:08:09.960 --> 00:08:13.030
When we're in a conflict,
our primate history,

00:08:13.030 --> 00:08:15.850
we tend to tighten the back
of our neck and our jaw

00:08:15.850 --> 00:08:17.020
and hunch our shoulders.

00:08:17.020 --> 00:08:19.110
And I could feel all
of that in my body.

00:08:19.110 --> 00:08:21.700
My solar plexus felt
like they were on fire.

00:08:21.700 --> 00:08:23.770
There could be a
sensation of nausea.

00:08:23.770 --> 00:08:26.642
And the whole time, my thoughts
are saying, this isn't OK.

00:08:26.642 --> 00:08:28.350
Why are these people
not listening to me?

00:08:28.350 --> 00:08:29.391
What is the problem here?

00:08:29.391 --> 00:08:30.370
They're all insane.

00:08:30.370 --> 00:08:31.537
I'm living in a madhouse.

00:08:31.537 --> 00:08:32.620
I don't like these people.

00:08:32.620 --> 00:08:33.900
I don't want to be with them.

00:08:33.900 --> 00:08:36.110
Now some tiny-- why
are you laughing?

00:08:36.110 --> 00:08:37.226
[LAUGHTER]

00:08:37.226 --> 00:08:38.309
Because you've been there.

00:08:38.309 --> 00:08:44.410
You know this demented voice
that just takes over, right?

00:08:44.410 --> 00:08:46.710
So my first thing
would be to just commit

00:08:46.710 --> 00:08:48.280
to experiencing the sensation.

00:08:48.280 --> 00:08:49.800
Stop the thoughts.

00:08:49.800 --> 00:08:51.240
Experience the sensation.

00:08:51.240 --> 00:08:52.550
Literally receive them.

00:08:52.550 --> 00:08:53.510
Get to know them.

00:08:53.510 --> 00:08:56.580
This is what this really
intelligent, evolutionary

00:08:56.580 --> 00:08:58.342
hardware is telling me.

00:08:58.342 --> 00:08:59.550
Like, what does it feel like?

00:08:59.550 --> 00:09:03.440
It's really organizing
me to get the hell out

00:09:03.440 --> 00:09:04.770
of here, basically.

00:09:04.770 --> 00:09:08.820
So once I could pace that a
little bit, and the sensations

00:09:08.820 --> 00:09:11.270
would start to calm down,
then I could pay attention

00:09:11.270 --> 00:09:12.560
to my thoughts.

00:09:12.560 --> 00:09:19.249
But even with the slightest kind
of attention-- it's amazing.

00:09:19.249 --> 00:09:20.790
What I'm trying to
say is how quickly

00:09:20.790 --> 00:09:22.450
the thoughts
reassert themselves.

00:09:22.450 --> 00:09:23.945
So I would quiet my thoughts.

00:09:23.945 --> 00:09:24.820
I'd be with the body.

00:09:24.820 --> 00:09:27.310
And as soon as I'd turn my
attention back to my thoughts,

00:09:27.310 --> 00:09:29.910
guess who was speaking again?

00:09:29.910 --> 00:09:32.742
Yeah, the demented, insane
person would start speaking.

00:09:32.742 --> 00:09:34.700
And so then I would just
pay attention to that,

00:09:34.700 --> 00:09:38.790
and I would say, OK, what
is the wisdom in this?

00:09:38.790 --> 00:09:41.650
What is actually right
about what I'm thinking?

00:09:41.650 --> 00:09:43.170
Because we have a
tendency when we

00:09:43.170 --> 00:09:46.670
get hijacked like that
to either be completely

00:09:46.670 --> 00:09:50.060
under the spell of the
insanity or completely,

00:09:50.060 --> 00:09:51.119
oh no, it's all fine.

00:09:51.119 --> 00:09:51.910
Well, actually, no.

00:09:51.910 --> 00:09:52.860
That's not the case.

00:09:52.860 --> 00:09:57.480
How do you find this middle way
where you receive the wisdom?

00:09:57.480 --> 00:09:59.780
So I would say, we
need more structure.

00:09:59.780 --> 00:10:01.752
We need to create
some patterns when

00:10:01.752 --> 00:10:02.960
we're having dinner together.

00:10:02.960 --> 00:10:06.030
We need to actually listen
to one another and exchange.

00:10:06.030 --> 00:10:09.400
So I really could
receive the wisdom

00:10:09.400 --> 00:10:11.140
from what I was upset about.

00:10:11.140 --> 00:10:14.410
And then when the thoughts are
now clarified, if you will,

00:10:14.410 --> 00:10:16.760
you receive and
clarify the thoughts,

00:10:16.760 --> 00:10:18.830
those thoughts
start to discipline

00:10:18.830 --> 00:10:20.780
the physiological responses.

00:10:20.780 --> 00:10:23.810
So then it's possible to go
back into the conversation.

00:10:23.810 --> 00:10:25.850
And even if you start
to feel the contraction

00:10:25.850 --> 00:10:27.560
or whatever those
are, you can sort of

00:10:27.560 --> 00:10:29.545
breathe that out
and still assert

00:10:29.545 --> 00:10:32.800
what is it that's important
around what I have to say

00:10:32.800 --> 00:10:37.230
and this whole body of
conflict resolution skills.

00:10:37.230 --> 00:10:39.740
So what I really want
to do is, in the book,

00:10:39.740 --> 00:10:41.850
give you an
opportunity to consider

00:10:41.850 --> 00:10:44.580
the evolution of
the body, consider

00:10:44.580 --> 00:10:47.690
how to work with the benefits
of meditation practice.

00:10:47.690 --> 00:10:49.270
And if you think
about meditation,

00:10:49.270 --> 00:10:51.870
really, as an inner
technology-- that's

00:10:51.870 --> 00:10:54.690
what it is, because you're
used to thinking in terms

00:10:54.690 --> 00:10:57.200
of the innovations--
well, meditation

00:10:57.200 --> 00:11:01.030
is one of the great ways that we
have of navigating our interior

00:11:01.030 --> 00:11:03.720
and heightening the
discipline, if you will,

00:11:03.720 --> 00:11:05.300
of how we perceive.

00:11:05.300 --> 00:11:12.160
And then I wanted to also, for
the-- meditative communities

00:11:12.160 --> 00:11:14.290
don't seem to have great
conflict resolution

00:11:14.290 --> 00:11:19.720
skills, because they don't want
to feel "the conflict," she

00:11:19.720 --> 00:11:22.525
whispered. (WHISPERS)
"The conflict."

00:11:22.525 --> 00:11:25.240
There is no conflict, right?

00:11:25.240 --> 00:11:28.230
So it all becomes kind of
passive-aggressive, right?

00:11:28.230 --> 00:11:32.000
So bringing conflict out
directly for the meditators,

00:11:32.000 --> 00:11:34.150
and for the mediators
to actually see

00:11:34.150 --> 00:11:37.240
how much meditation really
supports the mediation

00:11:37.240 --> 00:11:38.010
practice.

00:11:38.010 --> 00:11:40.970
So those were the two
sets of technologies

00:11:40.970 --> 00:11:43.550
that I was interested in
exchanging in the book.

00:11:43.550 --> 00:11:46.030
But as I got into
writing it, I also

00:11:46.030 --> 00:11:48.720
came to understand that there's
a third perspective that I

00:11:48.720 --> 00:11:51.520
think is really, really helpful
when it comes to really giving

00:11:51.520 --> 00:11:53.140
ourselves an
upgrade, if you will,

00:11:53.140 --> 00:11:56.890
or what do you call it when
you go from 2.0 to 3.0?

00:11:56.890 --> 00:11:58.100
Or where are you at now?

00:11:58.100 --> 00:12:01.030
I don't know,
Google-- what is that

00:12:01.030 --> 00:12:03.050
called when you go from
one level to another?

00:12:03.050 --> 00:12:04.180
Is that an upgrade?

00:12:04.180 --> 00:12:05.060
AUDIENCE: A release.

00:12:05.060 --> 00:12:06.393
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON: A release?

00:12:06.393 --> 00:12:06.908
OK.

00:12:06.908 --> 00:12:07.804
All right.

00:12:07.804 --> 00:12:08.700
Nice.

00:12:08.700 --> 00:12:10.490
I like that.

00:12:10.490 --> 00:12:15.280
So I realized that it was a
very incomplete discussion

00:12:15.280 --> 00:12:17.630
if I didn't also
include something

00:12:17.630 --> 00:12:20.500
about developmental theory,
meaning that there's

00:12:20.500 --> 00:12:22.620
a whole body of
research out there

00:12:22.620 --> 00:12:25.910
about how adult humans
grow and develop.

00:12:25.910 --> 00:12:27.350
We all know that children do.

00:12:27.350 --> 00:12:30.610
We all know that there are
certain developmental tasks

00:12:30.610 --> 00:12:32.650
that get accomplished
at certain ages.

00:12:32.650 --> 00:12:33.980
But the same is true of adults.

00:12:33.980 --> 00:12:37.700
We also can expand and
grow our perspectives.

00:12:37.700 --> 00:12:39.180
And the reason
that I got thinking

00:12:39.180 --> 00:12:41.700
about developmental
theory is because I

00:12:41.700 --> 00:12:45.330
was the director of dispute
resolution for the state

00:12:45.330 --> 00:12:46.790
judiciary in Utah.

00:12:46.790 --> 00:12:48.530
In other words, I
was responsible,

00:12:48.530 --> 00:12:51.810
back in the '80s, for creating
mediation programs in the court

00:12:51.810 --> 00:12:52.950
system.

00:12:52.950 --> 00:13:00.590
And I was a very
naive and Pollyanna

00:13:00.590 --> 00:13:05.860
and maybe "dumb" is just a good
word, in the sense that I sort

00:13:05.860 --> 00:13:08.230
of was under the impression
that if I just set up

00:13:08.230 --> 00:13:13.970
a nice environment, put some
tea and cookies on the table,

00:13:13.970 --> 00:13:15.530
that people could
come into the room

00:13:15.530 --> 00:13:17.290
and we could work
out the situation,

00:13:17.290 --> 00:13:19.430
whether it was a
barking dog dispute

00:13:19.430 --> 00:13:22.970
or whether it was a conflict
in a team, in an organization,

00:13:22.970 --> 00:13:25.190
or whether it was a
transactional dispute

00:13:25.190 --> 00:13:28.870
over land, a big land exchange
involving federal agencies.

00:13:28.870 --> 00:13:31.640
I assumed with enough goodwill
and the right structures

00:13:31.640 --> 00:13:33.260
and the right
conversation that we

00:13:33.260 --> 00:13:35.480
could get the problem solved.

00:13:35.480 --> 00:13:37.522
And guess what I discovered?

00:13:37.522 --> 00:13:39.990
That it wasn't
really quite true.

00:13:39.990 --> 00:13:41.900
And what seemed to be
at the heart of this

00:13:41.900 --> 00:13:44.650
for me was that I
started to see that there

00:13:44.650 --> 00:13:48.120
were limits to capacity.

00:13:48.120 --> 00:13:50.270
And the capacity that
I started to notice

00:13:50.270 --> 00:13:53.000
was the capacity to
take perspectives.

00:13:53.000 --> 00:13:55.375
And it wasn't
necessarily pathology.

00:13:55.375 --> 00:13:58.690
You know, I wasn't seeing
people who were sick and wrong

00:13:58.690 --> 00:14:01.470
or people who would
have a DSM-III diagnosis

00:14:01.470 --> 00:14:02.860
in the psychological world.

00:14:02.860 --> 00:14:04.600
What I was seeing was
just a whole range

00:14:04.600 --> 00:14:07.440
of people who had
different capacity

00:14:07.440 --> 00:14:09.030
to take different
points of view.

00:14:09.030 --> 00:14:12.190
So I worked with people who
came to me as a mediator who

00:14:12.190 --> 00:14:15.230
literally could not take
their own perspective,

00:14:15.230 --> 00:14:16.260
for whatever reason.

00:14:16.260 --> 00:14:18.690
Maybe they were in an
abusive relationship

00:14:18.690 --> 00:14:21.040
and it had been so long since
someone really asked them

00:14:21.040 --> 00:14:22.320
what they thought.

00:14:22.320 --> 00:14:25.000
I saw people who
were in a culture

00:14:25.000 --> 00:14:28.190
where because they were young,
maybe their opinion didn't

00:14:28.190 --> 00:14:31.370
matter, so they didn't
feel free to speak up.

00:14:31.370 --> 00:14:33.860
There were just some
people who simply had not

00:14:33.860 --> 00:14:36.820
been valued fully enough
to actually realize

00:14:36.820 --> 00:14:39.210
that they had their
own point of view.

00:14:39.210 --> 00:14:41.140
So I would work with
people all the time

00:14:41.140 --> 00:14:44.040
under the assumption that
I was facilitating people

00:14:44.040 --> 00:14:46.206
into agreement, but
there was one person

00:14:46.206 --> 00:14:48.080
who was incredibly
disadvantaged because they

00:14:48.080 --> 00:14:49.580
couldn't advocate
for themselves.

00:14:49.580 --> 00:14:51.100
Does that makes sense?

00:14:51.100 --> 00:14:54.540
So like I say, it started
to look developmental to me.

00:14:54.540 --> 00:14:56.880
I didn't want to
pathologize these people.

00:14:56.880 --> 00:14:59.340
It was a capacity that
wasn't quite online.

00:14:59.340 --> 00:15:00.527
Does that make sense?

00:15:00.527 --> 00:15:02.110
Then there was a
whole slew of people,

00:15:02.110 --> 00:15:04.137
of course, who could
come into mediation,

00:15:04.137 --> 00:15:05.720
they could take their
own perspective,

00:15:05.720 --> 00:15:08.800
but whose couldn't they take?

00:15:08.800 --> 00:15:10.530
Person on the other side.

00:15:10.530 --> 00:15:12.790
Like even to try
it on for a moment.

00:15:12.790 --> 00:15:15.470
There was no
bandwidth, if you will,

00:15:15.470 --> 00:15:17.520
to hold another perspective.

00:15:17.520 --> 00:15:19.990
Because as soon as we
have my perspective

00:15:19.990 --> 00:15:22.670
and I'm considering
yours, what happens

00:15:22.670 --> 00:15:26.536
in the body and the mind when
there are two perspectives?

00:15:26.536 --> 00:15:28.160
What happens when
there are two-- maybe

00:15:28.160 --> 00:15:29.076
engineers can help me.

00:15:29.076 --> 00:15:32.570
If there are two
oppositional qualities, what?

00:15:32.570 --> 00:15:33.890
AUDIENCE: Cognitive dissonance.

00:15:33.890 --> 00:15:36.510
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON: There's
cognitive dissonance, right?

00:15:36.510 --> 00:15:40.320
There's also an
energetic disequilibrium.

00:15:40.320 --> 00:15:44.410
There's actually a pole in which
energy can run between the two

00:15:44.410 --> 00:15:47.100
and disrupt or upset the system.

00:15:47.100 --> 00:15:48.940
Now, I'm kind of
trying to present

00:15:48.940 --> 00:15:51.340
that that's a good
thing, right, to be

00:15:51.340 --> 00:15:53.180
able to feel that
cognitive dissonance

00:15:53.180 --> 00:15:55.530
or feel that-- I don't know.

00:15:55.530 --> 00:15:57.520
I want you to help me
because you're actually

00:15:57.520 --> 00:16:01.240
trained in physics, and I'm not.

00:16:01.240 --> 00:16:04.010
But whatever that is, if
you have two coexisting

00:16:04.010 --> 00:16:06.070
truths in your head
at any one time,

00:16:06.070 --> 00:16:09.040
you literally have to deal with
the disruption in your body.

00:16:09.040 --> 00:16:10.820
So what do we tend to do?

00:16:10.820 --> 00:16:13.200
We tend to push one
out right away, right?

00:16:13.200 --> 00:16:15.100
Now, if you look at
your average news

00:16:15.100 --> 00:16:17.940
channel on a daily basis,
how many points of view

00:16:17.940 --> 00:16:20.009
are they able to hold?

00:16:20.009 --> 00:16:22.550
They set it up as though they're
going to hold multiple ones.

00:16:22.550 --> 00:16:25.790
And certain facilitator-type
newscasters will.

00:16:25.790 --> 00:16:28.880
But lots of time what you get
is a collapse of perspectives.

00:16:28.880 --> 00:16:31.800
And you get one sound bite
that just can be repeated again

00:16:31.800 --> 00:16:34.520
and again and again,
because we find security,

00:16:34.520 --> 00:16:36.300
because it's a single
truth, because it

00:16:36.300 --> 00:16:37.950
doesn't create ambiguity.

00:16:37.950 --> 00:16:40.000
And I saw lots
and lots of people

00:16:40.000 --> 00:16:41.390
who were capable of that.

00:16:41.390 --> 00:16:44.450
They could hold one truth,
but they couldn't hold two.

00:16:44.450 --> 00:16:45.400
Right?

00:16:45.400 --> 00:16:48.030
Then I started to
see these other kind

00:16:48.030 --> 00:16:49.390
of qualities in people.

00:16:49.390 --> 00:16:52.160
I would see people who
could have no point of view

00:16:52.160 --> 00:16:54.200
for a long period
and be really quiet,

00:16:54.200 --> 00:16:58.310
then I could see them really
very effectively advocate

00:16:58.310 --> 00:16:59.350
for themselves.

00:16:59.350 --> 00:17:01.950
And then I could see them
actually drop their position

00:17:01.950 --> 00:17:04.470
and listen to what
someone else had to say,

00:17:04.470 --> 00:17:06.310
and not simply listen
to it, but actually

00:17:06.310 --> 00:17:08.700
identify with it for
a period of time.

00:17:08.700 --> 00:17:12.180
And then I saw people who
could do even a greater trick.

00:17:12.180 --> 00:17:14.450
They could take a third
person perspective.

00:17:14.450 --> 00:17:18.680
So I, you, it-- they could think
about what a court would do.

00:17:18.680 --> 00:17:21.390
They could think about what
a legal interpretation might

00:17:21.390 --> 00:17:22.280
bring to it.

00:17:22.280 --> 00:17:25.187
They could think about a
social impact on the problem.

00:17:25.187 --> 00:17:27.270
And then, suddenly, there
was a much smaller group

00:17:27.270 --> 00:17:28.960
of people who not
only could they

00:17:28.960 --> 00:17:33.570
hold one, two, perhaps three,
they could hold four, five, six

00:17:33.570 --> 00:17:34.830
perspectives at once.

00:17:34.830 --> 00:17:36.937
They could take a
perspective on the process.

00:17:36.937 --> 00:17:39.020
They could think about how
the process had evolved

00:17:39.020 --> 00:17:41.150
from the past and where
it might go in the future.

00:17:41.150 --> 00:17:43.524
They could think about what
the impact of the facilitator

00:17:43.524 --> 00:17:44.640
was on the process.

00:17:44.640 --> 00:17:47.170
And I started to
say, oh my gosh.

00:17:47.170 --> 00:17:49.650
This is really important.

00:17:49.650 --> 00:17:54.470
This perspective taking, and the
capacity to take perspectives,

00:17:54.470 --> 00:17:58.700
changes the heart of negotiation
at such a fundamental level.

00:17:58.700 --> 00:18:02.390
And we as mediators aren't
even taking it into account.

00:18:02.390 --> 00:18:05.270
We don't even screen for the
number of perspectives somebody

00:18:05.270 --> 00:18:06.210
can take.

00:18:06.210 --> 00:18:08.450
Now I'm assuming
that in your teams,

00:18:08.450 --> 00:18:10.740
that you're pretty good at
throwing the ball around.

00:18:10.740 --> 00:18:12.880
Is that fair?

00:18:12.880 --> 00:18:13.380
Uh-oh.

00:18:16.090 --> 00:18:18.270
I'm projecting a lot of
idealism on your culture,

00:18:18.270 --> 00:18:20.240
so just say yes.

00:18:20.240 --> 00:18:22.330
Say, we're really good at it.

00:18:22.330 --> 00:18:26.070
And then, even more complex,
once you open up the field

00:18:26.070 --> 00:18:28.330
and can hold multiple
perspectives,

00:18:28.330 --> 00:18:31.680
you can hear different cultural
views on the same problem,

00:18:31.680 --> 00:18:33.750
you can see it from
many different angles,

00:18:33.750 --> 00:18:37.380
the further task is how then
do you privilege a perspective?

00:18:37.380 --> 00:18:39.670
What criteria do you
use to privilege?

00:18:39.670 --> 00:18:42.010
And then I'd see these
people that very seamlessly

00:18:42.010 --> 00:18:43.710
could privilege perspectives.

00:18:43.710 --> 00:18:46.740
And so I started to think
in terms of development.

00:18:46.740 --> 00:18:48.930
And shortly thereafter,
I was introduced

00:18:48.930 --> 00:18:53.590
to an American philosopher and
writer and amazing thinker who

00:18:53.590 --> 00:18:56.260
really has included a lot
of developmental theory

00:18:56.260 --> 00:18:57.250
in his work.

00:18:57.250 --> 00:18:59.450
And it really changed
my orientation

00:18:59.450 --> 00:19:02.140
to how I do mediation.

00:19:02.140 --> 00:19:04.950
Because I don't just assume
that everybody's capacity

00:19:04.950 --> 00:19:05.860
is the same.

00:19:05.860 --> 00:19:08.300
I assume that there are
differences in capacity

00:19:08.300 --> 00:19:10.650
and that I have to
take that into account.

00:19:10.650 --> 00:19:13.950
One of the really strange
sort of side effects

00:19:13.950 --> 00:19:15.820
of this difference
is that you would

00:19:15.820 --> 00:19:19.500
find people who were more
fluid with perspectives getting

00:19:19.500 --> 00:19:22.540
the short end of the stick,
in terms of the deal.

00:19:22.540 --> 00:19:23.129
Right?

00:19:23.129 --> 00:19:25.170
Can you think about what
I'm saying for a minute?

00:19:25.170 --> 00:19:29.320
Precisely because they could
hold more, they gave away more.

00:19:29.320 --> 00:19:31.090
And I started to think
there are actually

00:19:31.090 --> 00:19:33.280
ethical implications
to this issue.

00:19:33.280 --> 00:19:37.200
It isn't simply that you're not
able to hold my point of view.

00:19:37.200 --> 00:19:39.050
It's that when we
reach an outcome

00:19:39.050 --> 00:19:41.237
and it involves money, that
you walk away with more

00:19:41.237 --> 00:19:43.320
because you've been so
stubborn and you won't even

00:19:43.320 --> 00:19:45.770
pick up my perspective
on this whole thing.

00:19:45.770 --> 00:19:48.800
So I started to really feel like
there were lots of implications

00:19:48.800 --> 00:19:51.810
to this that I really
needed to consider.

00:19:51.810 --> 00:19:53.840
So if you're interested
in this book,

00:19:53.840 --> 00:19:57.390
you'll find some chapters that
talk about this innate capacity

00:19:57.390 --> 00:20:01.780
and also our ability to work
with complexity, which I know.

00:20:01.780 --> 00:20:04.290
And the more complex
our situation

00:20:04.290 --> 00:20:07.120
and the capacity for
working with complexity

00:20:07.120 --> 00:20:09.580
from developmental
theory, you could say,

00:20:09.580 --> 00:20:13.329
is one of the characteristics
of higher levels of development,

00:20:13.329 --> 00:20:14.620
if you want to put it that way.

00:20:14.620 --> 00:20:17.170
Now don't think about
higher levels of development

00:20:17.170 --> 00:20:20.030
in terms of social
dominator hierarchies.

00:20:20.030 --> 00:20:21.080
That's not the point.

00:20:21.080 --> 00:20:24.860
It's more like the way in which
an atom becomes a molecule

00:20:24.860 --> 00:20:26.280
and becomes more complex.

00:20:26.280 --> 00:20:28.800
And then a molecule
becomes a cell,

00:20:28.800 --> 00:20:30.400
and that becomes more complex.

00:20:30.400 --> 00:20:32.880
So holding perspectives
is like that.

00:20:32.880 --> 00:20:33.574
It's holonic.

00:20:33.574 --> 00:20:35.240
It's not just simply
that you're somehow

00:20:35.240 --> 00:20:36.780
better than the other person.

00:20:36.780 --> 00:20:38.170
That's not the point.

00:20:38.170 --> 00:20:39.210
OK?

00:20:39.210 --> 00:20:42.980
So are you interested in maybe
just tasting a little bit

00:20:42.980 --> 00:20:45.330
about how your perspectives
may have evolved?

00:20:45.330 --> 00:20:47.780
I could take you through
a series of perspectives

00:20:47.780 --> 00:20:49.610
that you could try on.

00:20:49.610 --> 00:20:50.211
OK.

00:20:50.211 --> 00:20:50.710
All right.

00:20:50.710 --> 00:20:53.899
So let me just present it.

00:20:53.899 --> 00:20:55.440
And for those of
you who are actually

00:20:55.440 --> 00:20:58.830
watching the live stream,
if you have a piece of paper

00:20:58.830 --> 00:21:00.250
and maybe a pencil,
and you might

00:21:00.250 --> 00:21:02.250
want to write this down
and just explore this

00:21:02.250 --> 00:21:03.430
while you're by yourselves.

00:21:03.430 --> 00:21:05.971
But maybe you could circle up
with the person who's near you.

00:21:05.971 --> 00:21:08.050
And I could just
invite you to try

00:21:08.050 --> 00:21:10.650
on a perspective,
exchange with each other.

00:21:10.650 --> 00:21:13.000
And then I'll say
"stop," and then we'll

00:21:13.000 --> 00:21:14.060
go to the next level.

00:21:14.060 --> 00:21:16.415
And you'll feel your
perspectives expand.

00:21:16.415 --> 00:21:18.040
And then we'll get
a little bit bigger,

00:21:18.040 --> 00:21:19.390
and then we'll get even bigger.

00:21:19.390 --> 00:21:21.770
So we'll do four
rounds of perspectives.

00:21:21.770 --> 00:21:23.610
Is that interesting to you?

00:21:23.610 --> 00:21:25.670
Do you like the person
you're sitting next to?

00:21:25.670 --> 00:21:28.700
[LAUGHTER]

00:21:28.700 --> 00:21:29.200
All right.

00:21:29.200 --> 00:21:32.060
I'm not going to try
to solve that problem.

00:21:32.060 --> 00:21:33.460
I'm going to leave that to you.

00:21:33.460 --> 00:21:35.970
Adam tells me you're
very capable here.

00:21:35.970 --> 00:21:40.840
So let's think for a
moment about the boundary

00:21:40.840 --> 00:21:41.615
around identity.

00:21:41.615 --> 00:21:43.240
So we're going to
think about identity.

00:21:43.240 --> 00:21:46.070
And we're going to
think of identity

00:21:46.070 --> 00:21:49.240
for a moment as a
set of perspectives

00:21:49.240 --> 00:21:52.450
so that who I am as Diane is
actually a set of perspectives.

00:21:52.450 --> 00:21:53.950
It's a set of memories.

00:21:53.950 --> 00:21:56.670
It's a relationship that
I have to this form.

00:21:56.670 --> 00:21:59.410
It's a set of relationships,
some of which have persisted,

00:21:59.410 --> 00:22:01.330
some of which have changed.

00:22:01.330 --> 00:22:02.860
It's a set of values.

00:22:02.860 --> 00:22:04.440
But those values
have also changed.

00:22:04.440 --> 00:22:07.030
So all those perspectives,
from one point of view,

00:22:07.030 --> 00:22:09.610
make up who I think I am.

00:22:09.610 --> 00:22:11.190
So I'm going to
ask you to explore

00:22:11.190 --> 00:22:13.114
the egocentric perspective.

00:22:13.114 --> 00:22:15.280
But I don't want you to do
it from the point of view

00:22:15.280 --> 00:22:17.410
that the ego is a bad thing.

00:22:17.410 --> 00:22:18.890
Do you get what I'm saying?

00:22:18.890 --> 00:22:22.510
Because lots of times, either
in our religious traditions

00:22:22.510 --> 00:22:25.900
or-- we think of the
ego as somehow bad.

00:22:25.900 --> 00:22:28.060
Why do we think
of the ego as bad?

00:22:28.060 --> 00:22:30.039
Can anyone help me with this?

00:22:30.039 --> 00:22:31.580
AUDIENCE: 'Cause
when it's in charge,

00:22:31.580 --> 00:22:34.134
it kind of makes people shitty?

00:22:34.134 --> 00:22:35.550
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON:
Yeah, people

00:22:35.550 --> 00:22:38.082
get-- there's just
something quite

00:22:38.082 --> 00:22:39.290
beautiful about what he said.

