00:32:27.800 --> 00:32:31.230
living next to me, and now all
of a sudden that little secure

00:32:31.230 --> 00:32:33.440
sense I have about
how the world is,

00:32:33.440 --> 00:32:36.490
suddenly I start to feel
like, oh, there's difference.

00:32:36.490 --> 00:32:38.670
And guess what the bright
line in development

00:32:38.670 --> 00:32:41.330
is between ethnocentrism
and world-centrism?

00:32:41.330 --> 00:32:42.240
Guess what it is?

00:32:42.240 --> 00:32:44.802
There are a few, but there's
one really significant one.

00:32:44.802 --> 00:32:46.166
AUDIENCE: Contact.

00:32:46.166 --> 00:32:47.540
DIANE MUSHO
HAMILTON: Difference.

00:32:47.540 --> 00:32:49.810
At world-centric,
difference is embraced.

00:32:49.810 --> 00:32:53.130
At ethnocentric,
difference is threatening.

00:32:53.130 --> 00:32:55.570
Does everybody see that?

00:32:55.570 --> 00:32:59.770
So you can almost-- it
would be inaccurate to do,

00:32:59.770 --> 00:33:04.000
but you can almost kind of
feel a culture, in terms

00:33:04.000 --> 00:33:06.780
of how many perspectives
this can take,

00:33:06.780 --> 00:33:09.030
on what its relationship
to diversity is.

00:33:09.030 --> 00:33:10.830
Does that make sense?

00:33:10.830 --> 00:33:11.330
Yeah?

00:33:11.330 --> 00:33:12.955
AUDIENCE: What did
you mean by the term

00:33:12.955 --> 00:33:15.194
"shadow," in terms
of the ethnocentric?

00:33:15.194 --> 00:33:18.800
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON: So in
order to maintain an identity,

00:33:18.800 --> 00:33:21.920
there are things that I
have to keep out of it.

00:33:21.920 --> 00:33:23.230
Does that make sense?

00:33:23.230 --> 00:33:27.350
So Jung referred to the shadow
as anything that I cannot bring

00:33:27.350 --> 00:33:29.930
into my identity as me.

00:33:29.930 --> 00:33:33.730
So I used to do lots of
conversations on race.

00:33:33.730 --> 00:33:37.460
Race and race
relations, just issues

00:33:37.460 --> 00:33:39.280
related to ethnic identity.

00:33:39.280 --> 00:33:43.730
And when the identity is
strong, necessarily there

00:33:43.730 --> 00:33:46.460
are things that are
left outside of it.

00:33:46.460 --> 00:33:49.280
So as Diane, I'm
doing a mediation.

00:33:49.280 --> 00:33:50.630
A woman gets upset.

00:33:50.630 --> 00:33:52.370
She tells me that
she's upset with me

00:33:52.370 --> 00:33:54.760
because I'm flirting
with her husband.

00:33:54.760 --> 00:33:57.500
And what is my first response?

00:33:57.500 --> 00:34:00.050
I'm not a flirt.

00:34:00.050 --> 00:34:01.550
I would never do that, right?

00:34:01.550 --> 00:34:02.520
Not me.

00:34:02.520 --> 00:34:04.030
It's the not me.

00:34:04.030 --> 00:34:07.299
So what happens is the
not me starts to encroach.

00:34:07.299 --> 00:34:09.840
The not me start-- and you start
saying, well, wait a minute.

00:34:09.840 --> 00:34:11.730
Is that really not me?

00:34:11.730 --> 00:34:14.500
Maybe there's more of me
than I thought there was.

00:34:14.500 --> 00:34:16.080
Maybe I am a flirt.

00:34:16.080 --> 00:34:16.850
You're right.

00:34:16.850 --> 00:34:17.380
It's true.

00:34:17.380 --> 00:34:19.460
I want to marry your
soon-to-be ex-husband.

00:34:19.460 --> 00:34:22.892
No, that's not [INAUDIBLE].

00:34:22.892 --> 00:34:24.600
I said, you're the
fool that married him,

00:34:24.600 --> 00:34:26.224
and now I have to
mediate your divorce.

00:34:26.224 --> 00:34:28.789
Leave me alone.

00:34:28.789 --> 00:34:30.330
But it's just
basically anything that

00:34:30.330 --> 00:34:33.590
comes in that we can't
hold as I. It's not me.

00:34:33.590 --> 00:34:36.159
It's a very famous thing
that we say that when

00:34:36.159 --> 00:34:38.080
human beings go to
war with each other,

00:34:38.080 --> 00:34:41.380
that one of the first things
we do is dehumanize the enemy.

00:34:41.380 --> 00:34:43.650
Because the enemy
has to become not me.

00:34:43.650 --> 00:34:45.530
If it's not me, then
I can abuse you.

00:34:45.530 --> 00:34:46.290
I can kill you.

00:34:46.290 --> 00:34:47.429
I can destroy you.

00:34:47.429 --> 00:34:51.510
But as soon as you're like
me, I no longer can do that.

00:34:51.510 --> 00:34:53.570
So that boundary
around what's me

00:34:53.570 --> 00:34:57.720
and what's not me at
ethnocentric is strong.

00:34:57.720 --> 00:35:02.430
And it can be kind of
confusing to suddenly start

00:35:02.430 --> 00:35:04.330
to want to move,
or naturally move,

00:35:04.330 --> 00:35:06.290
to a world-centric
level of development,

00:35:06.290 --> 00:35:08.870
because you don't want
to necessarily push away

00:35:08.870 --> 00:35:09.540
your culture.

00:35:09.540 --> 00:35:11.429
But you don't
quite-- it's awkward.

00:35:11.429 --> 00:35:12.720
Have any of you ever felt that?

00:35:12.720 --> 00:35:15.096
Like, there's an awkwardness
in terms of that transition?

00:35:15.096 --> 00:35:16.553
And I'll tell you
a little bit more

00:35:16.553 --> 00:35:18.900
about that in just a moment
and how to work with that.

00:35:18.900 --> 00:35:22.290
So the shadow is really
the pressing in of things

00:35:22.290 --> 00:35:23.840
that we don't want to be me.

00:35:23.840 --> 00:35:26.700
So another example
would be, it might

00:35:26.700 --> 00:35:34.780
be that, traditionally,
being gay is not me, right?

00:35:34.780 --> 00:35:38.050
And then all of a
sudden, my brother's gay.

00:35:38.050 --> 00:35:40.170
And all of a sudden, my son is.

00:35:40.170 --> 00:35:43.240
And all of a sudden, all
the not me is now me.

00:35:43.240 --> 00:35:46.200
But the culture I'm in is
still saying it's not me.

00:35:46.200 --> 00:35:49.141
That's an interesting way
just to think about it.

00:35:49.141 --> 00:35:49.640
All right.

00:35:49.640 --> 00:35:51.650
So do you want to grow
now in your perspective,

00:35:51.650 --> 00:35:53.210
just get a little bit bigger?

00:35:53.210 --> 00:35:55.590
So this round, you're
going to identify

00:35:55.590 --> 00:35:58.430
as the world-centric self.

00:35:58.430 --> 00:35:59.930
And you're going
to feel, well, what

00:35:59.930 --> 00:36:01.880
does it mean to
be world-centric?

00:36:01.880 --> 00:36:04.810
In fact, we were down
in the juice bar,

00:36:04.810 --> 00:36:08.870
in the Wellness Center, and
I got a nice cup of juice.

00:36:08.870 --> 00:36:13.910
And guess what the name of the
label on the plastic cup was?

00:36:13.910 --> 00:36:15.195
World-centric.

00:36:15.195 --> 00:36:17.320
That's what it said.

00:36:17.320 --> 00:36:19.850
So you can identify as
the world-centric self

00:36:19.850 --> 00:36:21.760
and see what comes
into awareness.

00:36:21.760 --> 00:36:25.230
Just identify and let your
awareness do the work.

00:36:25.230 --> 00:36:27.242
What does it mean
to be world-centric?

00:36:27.242 --> 00:36:28.200
Two and a half minutes.

00:36:28.200 --> 00:36:28.908
Let's explore it.

00:36:28.908 --> 00:36:32.278
[INTERPOSING VOICES]

00:36:44.660 --> 00:36:49.370
So just as an interesting
form of exploration,

00:36:49.370 --> 00:36:52.100
as you identified as
the world-centric self,

00:36:52.100 --> 00:36:55.240
what came into awareness that
wasn't there when you were

00:36:55.240 --> 00:36:56.984
at an ethnocentric--
when you had

00:36:56.984 --> 00:36:58.150
another set of perspectives?

00:36:58.150 --> 00:37:00.950
What perspectives
suddenly came online?

00:37:00.950 --> 00:37:03.900
How about you guys in the back?

00:37:03.900 --> 00:37:05.300
Yeah?

00:37:05.300 --> 00:37:06.830
AUDIENCE: Scale.

00:37:06.830 --> 00:37:11.018
Often enough, I kind
of go back and forth

00:37:11.018 --> 00:37:14.477
between ego and ethno
[INAUDIBLE] communal, but not

00:37:14.477 --> 00:37:15.210
world.

00:37:15.210 --> 00:37:17.150
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON:
Right, right, right.

00:37:17.150 --> 00:37:17.650
Yeah.

00:37:17.650 --> 00:37:19.870
And yet I think it's
fair to say Google

00:37:19.870 --> 00:37:23.260
is a world-centric company,
in terms of its reach.

00:37:23.260 --> 00:37:24.394
Is that fair?

00:37:24.394 --> 00:37:25.170
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:37:25.170 --> 00:37:26.020
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON:
Yeah, I think so.

00:37:26.020 --> 00:37:26.520
Yeah?

00:37:26.520 --> 00:37:28.380
AUDIENCE: Well, in
my case, I feel--

00:37:28.380 --> 00:37:29.713
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON: Very good.

00:37:29.713 --> 00:37:33.380
So actually, my capacity to
identify with all of humanity

00:37:33.380 --> 00:37:35.410
and to really enjoy
the differences

00:37:35.410 --> 00:37:38.300
and to appreciate the
differences is fully online.

00:37:38.300 --> 00:37:40.540
One of the dilemmas
of being world-centric

00:37:40.540 --> 00:37:43.600
is that when you try to
speak world-centric language

00:37:43.600 --> 00:37:47.080
to people who are genuinely
embedded at ethnocentric,

00:37:47.080 --> 00:37:48.850
it's a developmental thing.

00:37:48.850 --> 00:37:49.940
It's not a moral thing.

00:37:49.940 --> 00:37:51.565
It's like telling a
toddler they should

00:37:51.565 --> 00:37:53.340
be able to run
better than they are.

00:37:53.340 --> 00:37:55.530
Now you have to kind of
try that on a little.

00:37:55.530 --> 00:37:57.070
Again, think about atoms.

00:37:57.070 --> 00:38:01.220
Think about complexity more than
about dominator hierarchies.

00:38:01.220 --> 00:38:03.000
But it is true that
what can happen

00:38:03.000 --> 00:38:06.420
is you are filled with this
expansive sense of look

00:38:06.420 --> 00:38:09.730
at-- identify with the
ecosystems and lots of species

00:38:09.730 --> 00:38:11.460
and what's happening
around the planet.

00:38:11.460 --> 00:38:13.450
And I want you to do the same.

00:38:13.450 --> 00:38:16.690
And when you don't, I overbear
on you in that kind of way,

00:38:16.690 --> 00:38:20.510
where then I become sort of
bigoted in a world-centric way.

00:38:20.510 --> 00:38:23.690
It's like I'm bigoted, but
with my own set of values.

00:38:23.690 --> 00:38:25.910
Is that resonating with people?

00:38:25.910 --> 00:38:27.950
That's one of the
tricky parts of it.

00:38:27.950 --> 00:38:30.260
Now, it is possible
when you start

00:38:30.260 --> 00:38:31.910
to look at these,
how does somebody

00:38:31.910 --> 00:38:33.090
work with perspectives?

00:38:33.090 --> 00:38:36.480
How many perspectives are
available in this conversation?

00:38:36.480 --> 00:38:39.520
You can sort of start to go,
like, how many perspectives can

00:38:39.520 --> 00:38:40.420
we get on the table?

00:38:40.420 --> 00:38:42.610
And we'll maybe go to the
limit of what's possible.

00:38:42.610 --> 00:38:45.010
And then kind of adapt
to working with that,

00:38:45.010 --> 00:38:48.610
instead of pressuring people
to take on perspectives they

00:38:48.610 --> 00:38:49.570
literally can't.

00:38:49.570 --> 00:38:53.000
They literally don't
come up, so to speak.

00:38:53.000 --> 00:38:55.850
And one of the questions
that psychologists

00:38:55.850 --> 00:38:58.420
are working with is,
why is it that people

00:38:58.420 --> 00:39:01.470
move to a world-centric
level, and why don't they?

00:39:01.470 --> 00:39:04.150
And why is it that 70%
of the world's population

00:39:04.150 --> 00:39:06.435
seems to be at more of
an ethnocentric level

00:39:06.435 --> 00:39:07.140
of development?

00:39:07.140 --> 00:39:09.181
In other words, a whole
other set of perspectives

00:39:09.181 --> 00:39:10.460
are not really online.

00:39:10.460 --> 00:39:13.450
And how can we include
that without devaluing it?

00:39:13.450 --> 00:39:18.600
Like, do we have to jettison
the whole developmental lens

00:39:18.600 --> 00:39:20.880
in order to treat
everyone equally?

00:39:20.880 --> 00:39:24.180
So there's this real kind of
complex developmental challenge

00:39:24.180 --> 00:39:26.600
that's in this body of work.

00:39:26.600 --> 00:39:29.480
And when I go back to
revisiting the naive mediator,

00:39:29.480 --> 00:39:31.759
she just wants everyone to
be the same and be equal.

00:39:31.759 --> 00:39:33.300
But she has to be
honest with herself

00:39:33.300 --> 00:39:36.480
that the capacity for taking
perspectives is not the same

00:39:36.480 --> 00:39:39.420
and that she's kind of up in the
night if she doesn't know that.

00:39:39.420 --> 00:39:41.200
Does that answer your question?

00:39:41.200 --> 00:39:43.250
If you'll bear with
me for a moment,

00:39:43.250 --> 00:39:47.622
I'm going to make an
assumption that the overriding

00:39:47.622 --> 00:39:49.080
number of people
at Google are sort

00:39:49.080 --> 00:39:50.770
of ethnocentric in
their sensibilities.

00:39:50.770 --> 00:39:51.326
Is that fair?

00:39:51.326 --> 00:39:53.700
In other words, you can take
an egocentric point of view,

00:39:53.700 --> 00:39:56.241
an ethnocentric point of view,
a world-centric point of view.

00:39:56.241 --> 00:39:59.770
And then you can
identify as a Googler.

00:39:59.770 --> 00:40:03.220
And as a Googler, is that
an ethnocentric identity?

00:40:03.220 --> 00:40:05.316
AUDIENCE: Yes.

00:40:05.316 --> 00:40:06.440
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON: Yeah.

00:40:06.440 --> 00:40:08.064
Well, that's what's
interesting, right?

00:40:08.064 --> 00:40:11.020
Because it has the qualities
of, well, this is my company,

00:40:11.020 --> 00:40:12.330
and I'm not that company.

00:40:12.330 --> 00:40:14.290
Or this is the
lifestyle I prefer.

00:40:14.290 --> 00:40:17.950
And then it has all the traits
of more of ethnocentrism.

00:40:17.950 --> 00:40:19.830
It doesn't have
the expansiveness

00:40:19.830 --> 00:40:22.350
that a genuine world-centric
perspective has.

00:40:22.350 --> 00:40:24.620
So in a way, what I
would invite you to do

00:40:24.620 --> 00:40:27.120
is just work with this
as a very loose framework

00:40:27.120 --> 00:40:29.810
to help you make some
distinctions but at no point

00:40:29.810 --> 00:40:31.680
regard this as truth.

00:40:31.680 --> 00:40:34.140
Because that starts to
limit, actually, the nuance

00:40:34.140 --> 00:40:37.010
and just the open
question that we

00:40:37.010 --> 00:40:40.570
have about how are
perspectives at play.

00:40:40.570 --> 00:40:43.777
So would you like to
go one more level?

00:40:43.777 --> 00:40:45.360
So I'm going to lead
you through this.

00:40:45.360 --> 00:40:47.244
I'm not going to have
you talk to each other.

00:40:47.244 --> 00:40:48.660
But I'm going to
actually lead it,

00:40:48.660 --> 00:40:51.850
and I'm going to touch into a
quality of mind and identity

00:40:51.850 --> 00:40:53.814
that maybe I'm going
to put a label on,

00:40:53.814 --> 00:40:54.980
and then we'll work with it.

00:40:54.980 --> 00:40:57.040
So what I'd like
you do is I'd like

00:40:57.040 --> 00:41:01.150
you to identify as the
cosmic-centric self.

00:41:01.150 --> 00:41:03.670
We're going to actually
transcend world-centric,

00:41:03.670 --> 00:41:07.330
and you're going to
become cosmic-centric.

00:41:07.330 --> 00:41:10.640
Now keep in mind,
cosmic-centric includes world.

00:41:10.640 --> 00:41:12.410
It includes healthy
ethnocentrism--

00:41:12.410 --> 00:41:16.400
healthy-- and
healthy egocentric.

00:41:16.400 --> 00:41:17.580
So who am I speaking to?

00:41:17.580 --> 00:41:19.119
Who are you?

00:41:19.119 --> 00:41:20.160
AUDIENCE: Cosmic-centric.

00:41:20.160 --> 00:41:22.243
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON: I'm
the cosmic-centric self.

00:41:22.243 --> 00:41:24.450
So just identify as the
cosmic-centric self.

00:41:24.450 --> 00:41:26.660
And can I ask you a question?

00:41:26.660 --> 00:41:31.620
As the cosmic-centric
self, how big are you?

00:41:31.620 --> 00:41:34.380
Where is that
boundary of identity?

00:41:34.380 --> 00:41:37.070
You're limitless.

00:41:37.070 --> 00:41:38.260
So you said limitless.

00:41:38.260 --> 00:41:38.870
Anyone else?

00:41:38.870 --> 00:41:39.620
AUDIENCE: Endless.

00:41:39.620 --> 00:41:41.578
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON:
"Endless" is a good word.

00:41:41.578 --> 00:41:42.900
"Vast" is a good word.

00:41:42.900 --> 00:41:44.170
Just, whoa!

00:41:44.170 --> 00:41:47.900
But keep in mind, to the ego,
that feels very overwhelming.

00:41:47.900 --> 00:41:52.030
Because the ego
wants its boundaries.

00:41:52.030 --> 00:41:52.530
All right.

00:41:52.530 --> 00:41:57.010
So as the cosmic-centric
self, when were you born?

00:41:57.010 --> 00:41:59.240
13-- you guys keep
changing the number.

00:41:59.240 --> 00:42:03.460
13.5, 13.7, 13.8.

00:42:03.460 --> 00:42:05.860
Could you even say-- and
this is for you-- could

00:42:05.860 --> 00:42:08.020
you even say if we
just looked at space,

00:42:08.020 --> 00:42:13.370
and we said, I'm
limitless space actually--

00:42:13.370 --> 00:42:16.120
I can't quite identify
the boundaries of space.

00:42:16.120 --> 00:42:19.210
Can I also, as the
cosmic-centric self,

00:42:19.210 --> 00:42:21.931
feel beyond time?

00:42:21.931 --> 00:42:23.290
Yeah, can you feel that?

00:42:23.290 --> 00:42:24.420
Yeah.

00:42:24.420 --> 00:42:25.050
Good.

00:42:25.050 --> 00:42:26.340
AUDIENCE: I just want
to say, I feel like,

00:42:26.340 --> 00:42:27.200
as the cosmic-centric--

00:42:27.200 --> 00:42:27.920
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON: OK.

00:42:27.920 --> 00:42:29.680
He says, as the
cosmic-centric self,

00:42:29.680 --> 00:42:31.940
because I let down
my boundaries,

00:42:31.940 --> 00:42:33.960
I feel connected
with everything.

00:42:33.960 --> 00:42:35.880
And I notice there's
a sense of happiness.

00:42:35.880 --> 00:42:38.250
Nothing really feels
threatening to me.

00:42:38.250 --> 00:42:41.080
It's because identity
itself has dissolved.

00:42:41.080 --> 00:42:44.720
And when identity itself
dissolves, I'm completely open.

00:42:44.720 --> 00:42:48.720
And I'm relaxed in a way
that's really fundamental.

00:42:48.720 --> 00:42:50.930
I feel really at home.

00:42:50.930 --> 00:42:53.880
What is the practice
that we use to cultivate

00:42:53.880 --> 00:42:56.000
this quality of awareness?

00:42:56.000 --> 00:42:57.660
Meditation.

00:42:57.660 --> 00:43:00.440
So we don't give it that label,
because that label creates

00:43:00.440 --> 00:43:00.940
something.

00:43:00.940 --> 00:43:05.230
We actually just continually
drop identification.

00:43:05.230 --> 00:43:08.980
So as the cosmic-centric self,
what are your preferences?

00:43:08.980 --> 00:43:10.934
What do you prefer?

00:43:10.934 --> 00:43:12.350
AUDIENCE: Whatever happens.

00:43:12.350 --> 00:43:15.920
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON: I
prefer whatever's happening.

00:43:15.920 --> 00:43:18.720
That's awesome.

00:43:18.720 --> 00:43:20.825
Thich Nhat Hanh would be
very proud of this group

00:43:20.825 --> 00:43:23.930
if he were here right now.

00:43:23.930 --> 00:43:24.430
Yeah.

00:43:24.430 --> 00:43:25.301
Please.

00:43:25.301 --> 00:43:27.947
AUDIENCE: Present moment
awareness and objectivity.

00:43:27.947 --> 00:43:30.390
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON:
So because time changes,

00:43:30.390 --> 00:43:33.170
I no longer am referencing
past and future.

00:43:33.170 --> 00:43:36.170
I'm completely in the
here and now, right?

00:43:36.170 --> 00:43:38.190
And my awareness is wide open.

00:43:38.190 --> 00:43:39.540
There's no sense of limit.

00:43:39.540 --> 00:43:44.260
I'm not organizing awareness
around me or around you and not

00:43:44.260 --> 00:43:45.220
you, right?

00:43:45.220 --> 00:43:46.980
But my awareness
is just wide open,

00:43:46.980 --> 00:43:48.940
and I'm very present
in the here and now.

00:43:48.940 --> 00:43:50.760
Excellent.

00:43:50.760 --> 00:43:51.260
Yeah.

00:43:51.260 --> 00:43:54.250
He's saying I have a
preference for expansiveness

00:43:54.250 --> 00:43:55.870
over contraction.

00:43:55.870 --> 00:43:59.450
I have a preference for
emptiness over density.

00:43:59.450 --> 00:44:01.540
But actually, if I
really sit with it,

00:44:01.540 --> 00:44:04.470
I see that I am both of those.

00:44:04.470 --> 00:44:06.650
There's nothing that
is beyond what I am.

00:44:06.650 --> 00:44:09.790
So I'm simply embedded in
the breadth of all things,

00:44:09.790 --> 00:44:12.630
in the coming and the going,
in the up and the down-- and in

00:44:12.630 --> 00:44:14.862
the peace, but also
in the struggle.

00:44:14.862 --> 00:44:16.820
And that's really one of
the points of my book,

00:44:16.820 --> 00:44:19.210
is that when you really
do practice and learn

00:44:19.210 --> 00:44:21.970
to identify that
you can find peace,

00:44:21.970 --> 00:44:23.600
you can find that
quality of happiness

00:44:23.600 --> 00:44:26.400
that he's talking about, even
in the midst of challenge

00:44:26.400 --> 00:44:27.190
and struggle.

00:44:27.190 --> 00:44:31.610
So you become identified, if you
will, with your truest nature.

00:44:31.610 --> 00:44:34.510
So that's kind of
really the short course.

00:44:34.510 --> 00:44:36.920
And I'd be happy to take
two or three questions

00:44:36.920 --> 00:44:38.400
before we finish.

00:44:38.400 --> 00:44:40.090
AUDIENCE: Earlier
on, you mentioned

00:44:40.090 --> 00:44:41.970
being influenced by a
philosopher and writer.

00:44:41.970 --> 00:44:46.157
And I was curious if you
could share the identity

00:44:46.157 --> 00:44:47.240
and how that impacted you.

00:44:47.240 --> 00:44:48.365
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON: Yeah.

00:44:48.365 --> 00:44:49.340
His name is Ken Wilber.

00:44:49.340 --> 00:44:50.834
He's written about 30 books.

00:44:50.834 --> 00:44:53.000
They've been translated
into 30 different languages.

00:44:53.000 --> 00:44:54.280
They're all still in print.

00:44:54.280 --> 00:44:57.190
And you might want to call him
a meta-philosopher, that he

00:44:57.190 --> 00:44:59.870
was both, as a
young man, training

00:44:59.870 --> 00:45:01.910
to be a doctor and very
interested in science,

00:45:01.910 --> 00:45:04.030
but he had a deep
spiritual inclination.

00:45:04.030 --> 00:45:05.820
And his whole work
has been about trying

00:45:05.820 --> 00:45:08.130
to get those two things
to work together.

00:45:08.130 --> 00:45:12.530
So the largest book
he wrote on trying

00:45:12.530 --> 00:45:15.380
to create these connections
between the interior world

00:45:15.380 --> 00:45:19.420
and the exterior world
is called "Sex, Ecology,

00:45:19.420 --> 00:45:20.660
and Spirituality."

00:45:20.660 --> 00:45:22.250
It's a very big book, 850.

00:45:22.250 --> 00:45:25.800
But what he's trying to do is
name the challenges of our time

00:45:25.800 --> 00:45:30.750
and create the
links between, say,

00:45:30.750 --> 00:45:32.810
how we work with the
interior of the mind--

00:45:32.810 --> 00:45:34.720
awareness, psychology,
phenomenology--

00:45:34.720 --> 00:45:38.630
and how we work with
neurochemistry and the body.

00:45:38.630 --> 00:45:41.100
And so he's really
trying to create

00:45:41.100 --> 00:45:44.470
what we call an integral
inclusion of subject matter.

00:45:44.470 --> 00:45:47.177
AUDIENCE: And then are you also
drawing upon spiral dynamics?

00:45:47.177 --> 00:45:48.260
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON: Yes.

00:45:48.260 --> 00:45:51.145
I'm drawing on Clare Graves'
work, which I did through Ken.

00:45:51.145 --> 00:45:52.270
AUDIENCE: Great, thank you.

00:45:52.270 --> 00:45:53.170
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON:
You're very welcome.

00:45:53.170 --> 00:45:53.710
Yes, please?

00:45:53.710 --> 00:45:55.626
AUDIENCE: As someone who
did not grow up here,

00:45:55.626 --> 00:45:57.250
I feel terribly
advantaged in the fact

00:45:57.250 --> 00:46:00.140
that I have knowledge of
two different cultures.

00:46:00.140 --> 00:46:02.240
And I can pick from
two different places

00:46:02.240 --> 00:46:04.330
and select the best
of both the worlds.

00:46:04.330 --> 00:46:07.180
Having said that, at times I
feel disadvantaged in the fact

00:46:07.180 --> 00:46:10.700
that my ability to relate
with folks from back home

00:46:10.700 --> 00:46:12.580
and here is limited.

00:46:12.580 --> 00:46:15.100
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON: It opens,
but it also creates limits.

00:46:15.100 --> 00:46:15.750
Yeah.

00:46:15.750 --> 00:46:17.940
Other people in the room
who feel that way as well?

00:46:17.940 --> 00:46:20.190
That you feel like you've
got this flexibility,

00:46:20.190 --> 00:46:22.720
but now you can't relate
to either world fully.

00:46:22.720 --> 00:46:23.220
Yeah.

00:46:23.220 --> 00:46:24.120
I agree.

00:46:24.120 --> 00:46:26.550
AUDIENCE: So this is
more a practical one.

00:46:26.550 --> 00:46:29.350
Before, you were
saying about how

00:46:29.350 --> 00:46:31.650
we need to become
comfortable with conflict

00:46:31.650 --> 00:46:33.220
and become trained in that.

00:46:33.220 --> 00:46:35.512
And as a software engineer,
every code review,

00:46:35.512 --> 00:46:36.970
every piece of code
that I check in

00:46:36.970 --> 00:46:38.178
is reviewed by somebody else.

00:46:38.178 --> 00:46:39.547
And so I get that a lot.

00:46:39.547 --> 00:46:41.630
There's always this, oh,
no, you've done it wrong.

00:46:41.630 --> 00:46:42.210
This is horrible.

00:46:42.210 --> 00:46:42.793
This is awful.

00:46:42.793 --> 00:46:45.329
[LAUGHTER]

00:46:45.329 --> 00:46:46.370
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON: Ow.

00:46:46.370 --> 00:46:47.720
AUDIENCE: No, this is
a fact of life here.

00:46:47.720 --> 00:46:49.510
Everybody's good, and
everybody's picky.

00:46:49.510 --> 00:46:50.530
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON:
Just do like my son does.

00:46:50.530 --> 00:46:52.196
My son has Down
Syndrome, and he'll just

00:46:52.196 --> 00:46:54.780
go, "Ow," whenever I
complain or criticize.

00:46:54.780 --> 00:46:57.670
AUDIENCE: So just as
a practical matter,

00:46:57.670 --> 00:47:01.270
how would you
suggest somebody get

00:47:01.270 --> 00:47:03.360
skilled in this who doesn't
have this opportunity?

00:47:03.360 --> 00:47:05.072
You can't just say
to your brother,

00:47:05.072 --> 00:47:07.280
oh, jump out at me with an
axe every once in a while.

00:47:07.280 --> 00:47:08.363
DIANE MUSHO HAMILTON: Yes.

00:47:08.363 --> 00:47:11.179
Well, this is one of the things
that I address in the book,

00:47:11.179 --> 00:47:12.970
is that basically what
you're talking about

00:47:12.970 --> 00:47:15.011
is you're talking about
a third person discourse.

00:47:15.011 --> 00:47:20.330
You're talking about an
empiric, engineering issue.

00:47:20.330 --> 00:47:21.790
But what's not
being addressed is

00:47:21.790 --> 00:47:23.740
what's happening in the
second person, what's

00:47:23.740 --> 00:47:25.830
happening in the relational
domain between you

00:47:25.830 --> 00:47:28.145
and me when you're giving
me feedback about the work

00:47:28.145 --> 00:47:28.770
that I've done.

00:47:28.770 --> 00:47:31.560
So great, even if
you're 100% right,

00:47:31.560 --> 00:47:33.460
is there a way we can
do that where I just

00:47:33.460 --> 00:47:35.280
don't feel kind of
accosted but rather I

00:47:35.280 --> 00:47:37.472
feel really supported
and included.

00:47:37.472 --> 00:47:38.930
And I think with
that, what I'll do

00:47:38.930 --> 00:47:41.480
is I'll give it back to Adam,
because Adam works in People

00:47:41.480 --> 00:47:43.720
Dev, and he can actually
answer that question

00:47:43.720 --> 00:47:47.521
about how we can bring more
of that quality to your team.

00:47:47.521 --> 00:47:48.520
So thank you, everybody.

00:47:48.520 --> 00:47:49.340
And here's Adam.

00:47:49.340 --> 00:47:50.100
Thanks so much.

00:47:50.100 --> 00:47:53.750
[APPLAUSE]

